        "FlashCardBack": "<div><strong class=\"SmallText\">Securites Act of 1933 <\/strong><span class=\"MediumText\">-&nbsp; <\/span><span class=\"SmallText\">Requires that <\/span><strong class=\"SmallText\">new<\/strong><span class=\"SmallText\"> issues purchasers be provided with a detailed prospectus before a purchase was completed.<\/span><br \/><br \/><strong class=\"SmallText\">Securites Act of 1934<\/strong><span class=\"SmallText\"> <\/span><span class=\"SmallText\">- Regulates the <\/span><strong class=\"SmallText\">secondary<\/strong><span class=\"SmallText\"> <\/span><span class=\"SmallText\">market (trading of <\/span><strong class=\"SmallText\">issued <\/strong><span class=\"SmallText\">securities).&nbsp; Act also created the SEC to enforce securities laws.<\/span><\/div>\r\n<p align=\"justify\"><strong class=\"SmallText\">Investment Company <\/strong><strong class=\"SmallText\">Act of 1940 <\/strong><span class=\"SmallText\">- Authorized the SEC to regulate unit investment trusts (UITs) and managed investment companies (closed-end and open-end funds) plus variable products.<\/span><\/p>\r\n<p align=\"justify\"><strong class=\"SmallText\">Securities Investors Protection <\/strong><strong class=\"SmallText\">Act of 1970 <\/strong><span class=\"SmallText\">- Established the SIPC to supervise securities firms that get into financial difficulties.&nbsp; The SIPC insures investors against losses arising from the <\/span><strong class=\"SmallText\">failure<\/strong><span class=\"SmallText\"> of a brokerage firm.<\/span><\/p>",
        "SortOrder": 7
      },
